ent interrelation of the three moments of capital. The book's literary readings, meanwhile, make vivid the uneven texture and experience of capitalist modernity at large. Analyzing formally and thematically diverse novels—works by Fiston Mwanza Mujila, Marlon James, Jennifer Egan, Eugene Lim, Rafael Chirbes, Neel Mukherjee, Rachel Kushner, and others—Jelly-Schapiro evinces the different patterns of feeling and consciousness that register, and hypothesize a way beyond, the contradictions of capital. This book develops a new conceptual key for the mapping of contemporary theory, world literature, and global capital itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aCapitalism in literature. 0aCritical theory. 0aFictiony21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPostcolonialism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aMarxism.  acapitalism.  acomparative literature.  aexpanded reproduction.  apostcolonial theory.  aprimitive accumulation.  asynthetic dispossession.  aworld literature.40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363544940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503635449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503635449/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles